from_this_business.history: Baiano Pizzeria got its name from the Bahia region of Brazil--people from there are called "Baiano," explains Matos, who first moved to the United States in 1998. The only job he could get was as a dishwasher at the old Go-Getters pizza at 69 Gough St., which is where he learned his pizza-making skills. After putting himself through business school and opening a successful pizzeria, Matos has come full-circle, taking over the Go-Getters location (which moved up the street a few years ago) with his brother Ian, and making it their own.
from_this_business.specialties: Baiano Pizzeria-Sunset has been a family-owned and operated establishment since 2014 and locals know us as the place to go for delicious food, great service, and a good time, and we work hard to give them all three with every visit. Equipped with passion for great Pizzas and even better customer service Ian Matos loves owning and running Baiano Pizzeria. We are devoted to providing our customers with fresh, high quality ingredients in a clean, modern, friendly, relaxed atmosphere. If you are dining in, taking out, getting a delivery, or letting us cater your event, you can always count on us!

reviews.text:
Can order direct from them online for both pick up and delivery.

Pick up was fast and efficient. All of the food was well packaged and tasted just as good as we remembered.

Great at delivery- I always get the fried chicken over rice and boba milk tea. Friend chicken over rice comes with chili oil bamboo shoots, bok choy, and a little braised pork for the rice. Super good and consistent!! The chicken is like popcorn chicken and is super taiwanese. 

strawberry milk tea is also really good! it's real strawberries and is kind of thick but I like it

We pick up dinner from here at least once a week. It is just that good. And have you seen the online menu? THE TIP GENERATOR THANKS YOU. It's adorable. 

I can't decide whether I like the kimchi pork belly or pulled pork bao better, so we always get both. The xiao long bai are always perfect, and my husband really likes the ground pork over rice. I've never seen such consistent quality in such a small operation before. Ho Da La's food is delicious and their service is excellent. This has been true both before and during the first global pandemic of my life. 

I notice some reviewers mentioning the price of groceries here. Please note that Ho Da La's price per roll of TP is half the price of my corner store - whose job it is to sell the stuff - AND they had it in stock 10 days earlier than the store did. It's this kind of nimble ingenuity that keeps small businesses afloat in hard times. I support it. 

And for the record, we bought 4 rolls. :)

photos.caption: Tea Fresh Taro Milk Taro Milk Tea Popcorn chicken Braised Beef Noodle Soup Grounded Pork over Rice

reviews.text:
One of the restaurants that closed late enough for us night owls. Super cute vintage deco with tons of Taiwanese snacks (egg rolls, brown sugar milk bar... )
Highlights was their Fresh taro milk I asked for no sugar- forgot to take picture before I slurped the whole thing down I didn't add any toppings but it actually came with big chunks of Taro 
Taro milk tea was ok 
Beef soup noodle with rich but clean broth, beef were tender and noodles weren't over cooked- I ordered clear noodle 
Authentic pop corn chicken which taste different from the ones u get in Quickly which I preferred more 
Dumplings was good, skin could be thinner 
Rice was a bit to soft but the grounded pork was decent

After moving to the Bay Area a year ago, we have been looking for a good Taiwanese place, and this one is not bad. Not as good as places we've had in Houston though. 

We ordered the pork belly and pork chop plates. Protein servings are fairly generous and price is pretty good (as long as you order directly through their website or phone or in person rather than Grubhub!). However, a couple of things stood out as nontraditional, if that's what you are looking for. For one, no marinated egg, which we are used to. Also, they served the pork chop with chili bamboo shoots (which I actually like) rather than pickled greens (which I don't personally like but are more traditional and are present in the pork belly dish).

We dropped by after hiking at the Pirate's Cove trail. The fried rice ball was so good, crushed peanuts were crunchy and pairs really well together. The taro ball shaved ice was pretty ok, too sweet on the beans and not sweet on the balls. 

There's no dine-in option and might take a bit for the food to be done.

photos.caption: 3 Piece Taiwaness Pork Belly Gua Bao

reviews.text: I ordered braised beef noodle soup, 3 Taiwanese pork belly gua baos, popcorn chicken, and a milk foam black tea this weekend. I wasn't sure what I wanted so (as you can see), I got a bit of everything! Their beef noodle soup is my go-to spot in SF, it's soo good and has a perfect proportion of everything. The gua bao was also amazing. The pork belly is soft and the bao is fluffy af. The popcorn chicken itself is great too. and with the sauce? it's a new level of amazing! would definitely recommend. honestly, whatever you get will be great. I've been to this place a few times (also getting their mix gua baos, eating their rice dishes, etc) and it has never disappointed!
reviews.user_location: West San Jose, San Jose, CA

Make Your Own Shaved Ice. Those were amazing peanut and sesame balls. They were also frozen, so had to warm them. :P
Fried chicken skin. They gave it to us free. On the house. :)

reviews.text:
We tried this place weeks ago, and I finally got around to writing this review. 

We walked by this restaurant many times before, but never tried them. Then I read a Yelp friend's review and thought why not give it a try. So one day we ordered delivery.

My hubby is a big fan of bread, pancakes, wraps, burritos, sandwiches, etc. So it's not a big surprise to me when he goes for the beef wrap which is essentially a chinese pancake wrap with meat inside. He wants to see whether this measures up to his other favorite place. It's good but not his favorite.

I like wonton noodle soup, and missing it since the SIP started, so I got the wonton noodle soup. It was just okay. Not my favorite either. And I really wanted to like it. I also tried the make your own shaved ice. This restaurant gave us the options to put these black sesame gluttonous rice balls on them. They were hard as a rock when it arrived because they were frozen, but after I separated the ice with the ingredients, and I heat the frozen gluttonous rice balls in hot water and introduced them back to the now half watery shaved ice with the other ingredients like red beans (azuki), it was very yummy. This is definitely a food that should be eaten right away, and not delivered.

Food was nicely packaged when it arrived. Overall, pretty good experience, but I look forward to trying a dine-out experience with them rather than a delivery as I don't think what we ordered translated well in the delivery process.

photos.caption: braised beef over rice and popcorn chicken

reviews.text:
We got 3 items for delivery, custard steamed bao (piggy~), braised beef over rice, and popcorn chicken.
All of them were tasty.
The custard bao is cute, though it's expensive. I mean, they shape it like a piggy, I guess that's why it's expensive.
Braised beef rice is also great, love the sauce.
Popcorn chicken is also tasty, just wished that they're crispier. Though can't help much because it's delivery anyway.
Overall, will order more food from this place in the future.
reviews.user_location: South of Market, San Francisco, CA

reviews.text:
Solid 4 stars

Ordered thru Uber eats.  
Great packaging, food was hot and didn't even need to heat it up.  Saved half for next day.

Taiwanese sausage - not bad, a bit dry but it's tasty.

Fish ball/wonton soup with noodles -. Soup and noodles were very tasty.  Fish balls is good.  Wontons were too mushy.   You get 2 fish balls and 2 wontons.  I felt for the price if $15, one should get at least 3 or 4 wontons/fish balls.

Pork belly rice - yummy.  Definitely would get this if yearning for rice and fatty pork.

Everything was solid, definitely would order again.

Yummmyyyy!! This is a great place to go for Taiwanese food and snacks! They're half restaurant/ half little market with asian snacks. I got their fried pork chop over rice and damn.. that was so good. The pork chop was fried perfectly and the pork was still super juicy. I wish they had drizzled a little more of the meat sauce over the rice (under the pork chop) though. The pork belly was also super tender and the perfect combination of meat and fat. You could tell it was marinated for a while as well, exactly what you want in a Taiwanese pork belly. 
I wasn't a fan of the tempura but that's because it's just not what I was expecting. It's more like "fried squid ball" that you might expect in hot pots or something. I recommend they rename that item because it's a little misleading (to be fair they said it was the Taiwanese version of squid tempura but still, it's so far off I don't think it's a good comparison).
Regardless, this place was so yummy! And well worth the price. I'm excited to try more of their authentic Taiwanese dishes... it makes me want to go back to Taiwan again for a visit! But in the meantime, this restaurant will do.

Love this restaurant!
Authentic Taiwanese street food with unique decorations. Food is great and price is reasonable. I came here on Saturday afternoon, don't need to wait. HoDala must be the best Taiwanese cafe in SF!!

photos.caption: Popcorn chicken, 3 Piece Taiwaness Pork Belly Gua Bao, and rice bowl with pork and tea egg
The rice bowl (before it was mixed)

reviews.text:
Five stars for the pork belly buns, but four stars for the overall meal experience.

The star of the show is the pork belly buns. I could easily eat six of those! The pork belly had the perfect ratio of meat to fat, and the buns were plush and easy to chew.

The rice bowl with ground pork and tea egg was just OK. Needed more flavor... Unfortunately, it wasn't very memorable. The popcorn chicken was decent, but a bit dry. I wish they gave us a more generous serving of the sauce to dip the chicken in.

Staff was nice and food was served quickly. Restaurant is quirky and cozy; I really like its decor. 

All in all, If I was craving Taiwanese food, I'll come back here and order the pork belly buns.

Came for dinner with two other people and thought it was just ok. We got a lot of dishes to share, and they were pretty mediocre compared to other Taiwanese places I've been to. The pork belly was flavorful but a little dry. The dumplings and scallion pancake were both fine, but they came with sauces that were a little strange. The mac and cheese balls (kinda unconventional for a Taiwanese place) were pretty good, but they had bacon in them which was not a listed ingredient on the menu and thus a sad realization for my friend who doesn't eat pork : (
The lychee soju freeze was really good though --super strong lychee flavor and very sipable despite the shot glasses they provided us. Parking was not fun, but that's not too surprising given the area.

You can't compare to places down in LA/OC, but for SF, it's a decent option. We ordered a lot (as usual), and I'll put them into 3 categories:

Would order again: 
gua bao - we got the traditional pork belly, and when you add some of the pickled veg from the rice bowl to it, made it even better. I'd like to try their other ones next time

Depending on craving, could order again:
kong rou fan (braised pork rice) - I'd probably go for the lu rou fan instead next time
za pai gu (pork chop) - nothing too special, but a classic
green onion pancake - on the oily side

Would not order again:
zhu xue gao (pig's blood cake) - way too much crushed peanut on top
luo buo gao (radish cake) - didn't really like that these were fried, but they'd probably go well with beer
green onion noodle - didn't love the flavor of these

We also got some steamed bao for the little guy to eat, and these were good for that. And, finally, as if we hadn't eaten enough already, we also got dessert - mango shaved ice (HUGE! would prefer snow) and black sesame tang yuan (also came with quite a lot). While it's not the BEST Taiwanese food, I do hope it stays open and does well because we need some TW food options here! So because of that, 4 stars.

Decent but unfortunately not great. I ordered delivery for dinner and tried the Braised Beef Noodle Soup, Ground Pork Over Rice, Xiao Long Bao, and the Fried Chicken Over Rice.

My favorite entree was probably the ground pork over rice. The richness of the pork was offset nicely by the pickled mustard greens. My least favorite was unfortunately the xiao long bao - the skins were too thick and the meat had soaked up a lot of the broth. The braised beef noodle soup was okay, but too heavy on the tomato flavor. An overarching issue I had was with the quality of the meats, which I thought was sub-par. For example, the fried chicken was very breading-heavy (and whatever chicken I had was dry), and the pork was extremely fatty.

I do appreciate that the delivery was fast and the food was well-packaged. Not sure if I'll order again any time soon but it was worth a try!

I was craving something Asian and simple after my hike at Mt Tam and stumbled across HoDaLa on my search; I picked it because you could go as simple or as extravagant as you want in a meal, share things family style or not, and there are numerous options to pick from! I opted for their herbal spare rib which hit all the right spots. The spare rib was massive, had some fatty portions to it, and would be best shared between 2 but at that moment, homegirl needed protein so she devoured one whole order by herself, #noregrets. The soup was hearty and you could taste the herbal aspect of it but I wish there were more veggies or some herbal bits instead of just a few massive lettuce leaves. The scallion pancake was nice and extra crispy - no complaints there. 

Overall, HoDaLa is a great place for Taiwanese comfort food. Service was attentive and the format was truly chill and no fuss. Parking wasn't too bad...I highly recommend side streets or parking in the more residential areas for free 2 hour parking (if you're eating there pre-6pm).

Really love this place!!

The atmosphere is super unique and the decor is super cool. Food here is also super good - I usually order the beef noodle soup, minced braised pork rice, and green onion pancake. Their tea is also super yummy! A must stop if you're craving Taiwanese food!

This corner restaurant has been a lot of weird things over the past 5 years: Szechuan spot, chicken shack, strange-ass sushi. Today it is a nerdy Taiwanese joint.

I recently spent 10 days in Taipei, so I really got a chance to get a feel for the cuisine and city culture. Probably gave myself some kind of condition after all the night markets and beer. 

Everything looks good, but not everything truly is. 

Taiwanese pork gua bao is very good. The other iterations of gua bao are awful. The fried chicken gua bao is basically a frozen chicken nugget deep-fried to order. Unacceptable! 

The xiaolong bao were probably the worst I've ever had. I've never had skins so thick in my life. There was also no liquid in the dumplings. What's the point? 

The beer was a little upsetting. The Taiwan Beer did not taste like the Taiwan Beer I was guzzling constantly for 10 days straight. The honey beer was just honey added to the Taiwan Beer (they have honey beer in Taipei so I thought I was getting that). 

The fried squid sizzling plate was pretty good, but not enough to offset all the other issues. Portion siE was a bit tiny. 

Also, I forgot how ridiculously disappointing it is to eat in San Francisco. This city is not a food destination. It's a giant scam built up on years of manufactured hype. 

Quality and portion size has been dramatically reduced while prices have continued to climb. So you're left paying 4x more for stuff that is about half the quality. 

Oh well!

Solid spot for Taiwanese food in the Central Richmond! After a tiring and cold Sunday in the city, my friend and I stumbled in with a craving for hot and spicy soups. We got what we came for! I ordered the braised beef noodle soup, she ordered the tomato and beef noodle soup. The soup was a big portion size, and the broth really packed a punch with savory beef flavor and spices. I felt my soul revive with every spoonful.

Their snack and dessert food looked really good too. Maybe next time!
